### TITLE ###
NotInvertsRefinement
### DESCRIPTION ###
`if not (x == null):` should be equivalent to `if x != null:` -
truthy branch narrows x to non-null.
### INPUT ###
fn f(x: int?):
    if not (x == null):
        y = x
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  x @ 2:13 -> int?
  y @ 3:9 -> <no-type>
  x @ 3:13 -> int

# Symbol types
  f (fn): <no-type>
  x (param): int?
  y (local): int

# Diagnostics
  (none)
### TITLE ###
AndChainsRefinements
### DESCRIPTION ###
`if x != null and y != null:` should narrow both x and y to non-null
in the body. The right operand is evaluated with the left's truthy
refinement active.
### INPUT ###
fn f(x: int?, y: str?):
    if x != null and y != null:
        a = x
        b = y
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  x @ 2:8 -> int?
  y @ 2:22 -> str?
  a @ 3:9 -> <no-type>
  x @ 3:13 -> int
  b @ 4:9 -> <no-type>
  y @ 4:13 -> str

# Symbol types
  a (local): int
  b (local): str
  f (fn): <no-type>
  x (param): int?
  y (param): str?

# Diagnostics
  (none)
### TITLE ###
AndShortCircuitRightSeesLeftNarrowed
### DESCRIPTION ###
In `x != null and type_of(x) == "int"`, the right hand sees x as
non-null (left's truthy refinement). With base type int?, the
right operand's narrowing to int is still useful (type_of can
further refine within the non-null component).
### INPUT ###
fn f(x: int?):
    if x != null and type_of(x) == "int":
        y = x
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  x @ 2:8 -> int?
  type_of @ 2:22 -> dynamic
  x @ 2:30 -> int?
  y @ 3:9 -> <no-type>
  x @ 3:13 -> int

# Symbol types
  f (fn): <no-type>
  x (param): int?
  y (local): int

# Diagnostics
  (none)
### TITLE ###
OrFalsyBothFalse
### DESCRIPTION ###
`if x == null or y == null:` truthy = at least one is null (no
refinement we can express). Falsy = both non-null - narrows both
in the else.
### INPUT ###
fn f(x: int?, y: str?):
    if x == null or y == null:
        a = 0
    else:
        b = x
        c = y
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  x @ 2:8 -> int?
  y @ 2:21 -> str?
  a @ 3:9 -> <no-type>
  b @ 5:9 -> <no-type>
  x @ 5:13 -> int
  c @ 6:9 -> <no-type>
  y @ 6:13 -> str

# Symbol types
  a (local): int
  b (local): int
  c (local): str
  f (fn): <no-type>
  x (param): int?
  y (param): str?

# Diagnostics
  (none)
### TITLE ###
NotAndDeMorgan
### DESCRIPTION ###
`not (x == null or y == null)` should give us "both non-null"
via the Negate path - flipping or's WhenFalse into the outer
WhenTrue.
### INPUT ###
fn f(x: int?, y: str?):
    if not (x == null or y == null):
        a = x
        b = y
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  x @ 2:13 -> int?
  y @ 2:26 -> str?
  a @ 3:9 -> <no-type>
  x @ 3:13 -> int
  b @ 4:9 -> <no-type>
  y @ 4:13 -> str

# Symbol types
  a (local): int
  b (local): str
  f (fn): <no-type>
  x (param): int?
  y (param): str?

# Diagnostics
  (none)
